On January 17, 2021 skeletal remains of an Asian or Hispanic male were discovered off Richmond Terrace, near Mariner's Marsh Park in Staten Island, New York. His hair color and eye color is unknown. The male was found wearing a dark blue long-sleeve sweatshirt with a logo of "Baseball '01" on the front, a white T-shirt with "Island All Star Cheerleader" on the front, Route 66 pants, a black sports headband, black socks, and black Timberland boots. A lighter and brown wallet containing a 2005 calendar was also found with the male. Images displayed were created by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and were digitally enhanced to aide in visual identification and may not reflect the original item.

On December 10, 2020, the body of an unidentified female child was found in a wooded area in the Van Duzer Forest State Park in Lincoln County, Oregon.  The recovery location was near a rest area in the Scenic Corridor.  Based on the condition of the remains, it is suspected the child had been deceased for at least 30 days.  She is believed to have been between 6 and 10 years of age.  She was between 3'10" and 4'6".  Her hair was dark brown or black, 12 to 14 inches in length.  Race, weight and eye color are unknown.  The featured sketch was completed by a Forensic Artist with the Clackamas County Sheriff's Office and is a rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like in life.  Anyone with information should contact the Oregon State Police.

On October 26, 2020, the body of an unidentified white female was found in rural Graham County, Arizona.  The recovery location is in the Artesia area, approximately 10 miles south of Safford.  The Jane Doe is believed to have been between 13 and 17 years of age.  She had short, light brown hair and was approximately 5'1".  Weight and eye color are both unknown.  Clothing items found on or near the Jane Doe include a black gown/robe and a black hooded sweater with skulls on it.  The featured images have been digitally enhanced to aid in visual identification and may not reflect the original case file images.  Anyone with information should contact the Graham County Sheriff's Office's general number 928-428-3141 or, if you wish to remain anonymous, please contact Crime Stoppers at 928-428-2746 or text "GRAHAMTIP" to 79516.

On September 28, 2016, the body of an unidentified female was located off US Highway 93 near White Hills in an unincorporated area of Mohave County, Arizona.  This section of Highway 93 is heavily traveled and is a main thoroughfare between southern Arizona and Las Vegas, Nevada.  Based on the condition of the body, it is estimated she had been deceased for 1-2 weeks.  The Jane Doe is believed to be between 13 and 17 years of age.  She is believed to be Black or possibly biracial with some Hispanic admixture.  She had thick, curly black hair, approximately 5 inches in length.  Her fingernails appeared clean and manicured and there were remnants of pink polish on her toenails.  It is noted that possible orthodontic intervention was contemplated, possibly braces or something similar to Invisalign.  A ?Hollister? brand t-shirt was found near her body but it is unknown if it belonged to her.  Isotope and pollen analyses have revealed the Jane Doe may have been from or spent a significant amount of time in the Great Lakes area, New England area, Eastern Canada, Pacific Northwest or Southwestern British Columbia.  The featured reconstruction is an artist?s rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like.  If you have any information, please contact the Mohave County Sheriff?s Office, reference case number 16-35440 or the Mohave County Medical Examiner?s Office, reference case number 16-1674.

On August 15, 2016 landscapers observed a black backpack lying along a private drive off Plamondon Road in Wheaton, Illinois. A deceased baby girl infant was found inside the backpack. It?s estimated the infant had been deceased less than 24 hours. Forensic testing suggests she was Hispanic. Authorities identified a medication in her blood that treats epileptic seizures or different mood disorders in adults. It is believed that the infant?s mother was taking this medication during pregnancy. The level detected was a standard prescribed amount.  Inside the backpack authorities also found a red bath towel, a brown bathmat and matching brown toilet seat cover. Pollen testing of the evidence suggest that the items spent a significant amount of time in an urban area of Northern Illinois and possibly originated in the Southwest United States before coming to Illinois. The images featured are of the items discovered with the infant.

A skull of a young child was recovered in Pulaski County, Missouri on October 26, 2013. The skull was found in a wooded area approximately 30 feet off Highway 28 in Dixon. An anthropologist examined the skull and estimates that the child was 8-13 years old. Sex could not be determined. The lower jaw was not recovered with the skull but an exam of the upper teeth did not find any evidence of dental fillings or orthodontic work. The anthropologist noted the child was likely of Mestizo ancestry which is an admixture of Native American, Hispanic, Latino and Mexican. The above images are a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist that depicts what the child may have looked like in life. The artist used the skull to create two images of the child. One that depicts the child as a female and the other as a male. Since the lower jaw was not recovered the jaw is the artist?s interpretation and only an approximation.

On July 25, 2010, the body of an unidentified Hispanic male was located in a remote desert area known for migrant activity, approximately two miles south of North Komelik Village in Pima County, Arizona (Tohono O'Odham Nation Reservation).  It is believed he had been deceased a few days.  The John Doe is believed to have been between 16 and 18 years of age and was approximately 5'3".  He had wavy black hair, approximately 4 cm in length.  The John Doe was found wearing a pair of blue jeans, a pair of black socks with red and white stripes, a brown woven leather belt with a metal buckle, a pair of brown shoes (size 9) and a brown cloth bracelet.  He was in possession of a Mexican document containing the name "Manuel Pu Meregildo", however it is suspected he is of Guatamalan nationality.  He was found with two other deceased traveling companions who are associated with the names "Agustin Antonio Castro" and "Manuel Ortiz".  The featured reconstruction is an artist's rendering of what the John Doe may have looked like.  The additional photos have been enhanced to aid in visual identification and may not reflect the original case file images.  Anyone with information should contact the Pima County Office of the Medical Examiner, reference case number ML10-01481.

On November 28, 2009, partial skeletal remains of an unidentified male were located three miles south of Mile Post 103 on State Route 86 in the Sells vicinity of Pima County, Arizona on the Tohono O'Odham Nation Reservation.  The United States Border Patrol located the remains in a remote desert area under a Palo Verde tree.  It is believed the John Doe had been deceased for 6 to 10 months.  The John Doe is likely Native American or Hispanic.  He is believed to have been between 14 and 19 years of age and was approximately 5'6".  Weight, hair color and eye color are unknown.  Clothing items found near the remains include a shirt with hand-stitched or sewn hems on the sleeves, blue denim pants ("Golden Blue" brand) and a black leather belt with a silver buckle and bull rider design.  The featured photos have been digitally enhanced to aid in visual identification and may not reflect the original case file images.  Anyone with information should contact the Pima County Office of the Medical Examiner, reference case number ML09-02408.

On November 23, 2008 an unidentified female was found deceased in Fond du Lac County. She was located in a small creek near an abandoned farm off Skyline Drive, which is about 1 mile, North of Highway 28 and East of Interstate 41. It is estimated that she had been deceased for several months prior to being found and likely died during the Summer or Fall of 2008. The Jane Doe is 15-21 years old and thought to be Caucasian, but Hispanic and Native American cannot be ruled out. She had long light brown to dark blond hair. She stood between 4?10?-5?04? tall and weighed between 110-135 pounds. Her teeth were in good condition with good alignment. She had fillings in four of her bottom molars. Anthropological examination also revealed that she had Spina Bifida Occulta, but possibly never knew she had this condition. It is also suggested that she might have been knock kneed or pigeon toed, where her feet turned slightly inward. A well healed fracture to one of her left ribs was also found suggesting she suffered some type of injury earlier in life. The Jane Doe was found wearing a black shirt (size small) and jeans (size 3) as pictured above. The clothing was most likely purchased at a Family Dollar Store or general retailer. The first three images above are a reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and shows what the female may have looked like while alive.

On February 19, 2006 the body of an unidentified Hispanic male was found on the east side of the railroad tracks located at 8800 South Old Nogales Highway in Tucson, Arizona (Pima County). He was 6'0" and weighed 127 lbs.  He had black hair and brown eyes.  The John Doe's left arm is contracted at his elbow due to a large scar that runs from his upper arm to the mid-forearm.  He also has scars on his left thigh and left chest.  The word "Lulana" is tattooed on his upper right arm.  The John Doe was found wearing a blue collared button-down shirt with a black and yellow design across the chest ("No Boundaries" brand, size 2XL), dark denim pants ("Nautica" brand, size 34 x 34), a purple nylon jacket with a green and blue striped fleece interior ("Gear for Sports" brand, size Medium), a beige baseball cap with the word "METCON" on the front, a tan belt with the letter "J" on the buckle and a multi-colored cloth woven bracelet.  He was also wearing white shoes with the name "Jose David" written in blue ink on the right shoe ("Reebok" brand, size 12).  The featured reconstruction is an artist's rendering of what the John Doe may have looked like.  The additional photographs have been digitally enhanced to aid in visual identification and may not reflect the original case file images.  Anyone with information should contact the Pima County Office of the Medical Examiner, reference case number ML06-0314.

An unidentified male was found deceased behind an abandoned gas station along SR 109 just south of Interstate 70 in Henry County, Indiana. He had been deceased less than 24 hours. The male is described to be Hispanic, 17-24 years old. He stood approximately 5?2? tall and weighed 108 lbs. He had short coarse black hair and had a mustache and thin goatee. He had a small mole on his upper right shoulder and another on his lower back. He was found wearing a blue sweatshirt with ?Malone USA? written on the front, brown work pants underneath ?UConn? warm up sweatpants, white socks, white Reebok sneakers, and a white Duke baseball cap. The male also had old brace brackets still attached to some of his teeth from previous orthodontic treatment. The investigation revealed that this same male was seen making a purchase at a Wal-Mart in Reynoldsburg, Ohio two days prior to when his body was found. At the time he was seen driving a red vehicle. The image above is a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC forensic artists and depicts what the male may have looked like in life.

On 09/18/2003 at approximately 1:30 a.m. Anne Arundel County Police responded to the 1700 block of Severn Tree Blvd., Severn, MD, in reference to a shooting and possible abduction.  Officers determined that Lamarst Porter had been shot and abducted.  Porter was last seen in the company of two balck males who are believed to have forced Porter into his 1991 Lincoln Mark VII bearing Maryland Tag: L J T 0 3 3 and fled the area.  Evidence at the scene indicates that Porter was fatally injured.  Porters vehicle was recovered in the Glen Burnie area a few days after the incident. Lamarst's body has never been located. An unidentified female was found on March 25, 2003 in Alcoa, Tennessee. The female's skeletal remains were found along a creek in a small wooded area off Cusick Road near the Knoxville airport. It is estimated that she had been deceased anywhere between 8 months to 4 years. The female was 17-25 years old at the time of death. She stood between 5'4" - 5'10" tall. Small black synthetic braids were found near her body and thought to have belonged to her. The female?s teeth showed two unique characteristics. Two of her upper front teeth were missing prior to her death for several years. The remaining upper front teeth showed extreme flaring and would have protruded, sticking almost straight out. The female's lower law was not recovered and characteristics of her bottom teeth are unknown. The female was found with a blue fleece jacket and a white tank top with "I don't need a great deal of love, just a steady supple" written on the front. A digital reconstruction of the shirt is featured above. The other image displayed is a facial reconstruction created by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depicts what the female may have looked like in life. Since the lower jaw was not recovered the jawline is the artist?s interpretation and only an approximation.

This unidentified child was found on May 9, 2000 on private property next to Bear Brook State Park in Allenstown, NH. She was 2 to 4 years old at the time of her death, placing her birthdate between 1975-1977. She had slightly wavy brown hair. DNA testing has revealed she is primarily Caucasian with a small amount of Asian, Black and American Indian ancestry. The child had a slight overbite that may have been noticeable. An analysis of her bones suggest that she may have had anemia in life but this cannot be confirmed. The investigation has revealed that she is not from NH but most likely from TX, AZ, CA, or OR. DNA testing has confirmed her biological father is Terry Rasmussen, who also went by many aliases including Bob Evans. He is the primary suspect in her death but has since died. Her mother has not been identified or located. She is feared to be another victim. The images displayed are a facial reconstruction created by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depicts what she may have looked like in life.

On December 12, 1987, the skeletal remains of an unidentified male were discovered in an open field located on the southeast corner of the intersection of Simpson Road and Bryant Road in Logan County, Oklahoma. Due to the condition of the remains, the decedent is believed to have been deceased 1-2 years prior to discovery. The decedent had straight black hair, and a supernumerary tooth in excess of his top central incisor teeth. The decedent was found wearing blue jeans- size 30 x 30 ("WRANGLER" brand) with a plain leather belt, a ball cap type hat in camouflage print with writing ?United Roofing 272-0360". Also found with the remains were a pair of white athletic shoes with a blue and teal colored trim in men's size 9.5, a child's size 4 sleeveless shirt with wide red/white/blue horizontal stripes ("HEALTHTEX" brand), and a gold and silver quartz watch. The decedent is believed to have been of Asian descent, possibly also Hispanic and/or Native American.  The reconstruction featured above is an artist's rendering of what the John Doe may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Oklahoma State Bureau of Investigations, reference case #CR19970347.

On August 9, 1997, skeletal remains of an unidentified female were located in the area of 51st Avenue and Dust Devil Lane on the Gila River Reservation in Maricopa County, Arizona.  Based on the condition of the remains, it is believed she had been deceased between 6 months and 1 year.  The Jane Doe is believed to have been between 16 and 20 years of age and was Native American or Caucasian.  She was approximately 5'3" and had long dark brown hair, approximately 10 inches in length.  The Jane Doe either had a child or had carried a child to term.  All of her teeth were present with no dental work.  The skeletal remains of a horse were located nearby.  An ankle length skirt, black in color with white designs throughout, was recovered among the horse bones.  The skirt was one size fits all and "Countess" brand.  Another piece of cloth, black with white polka dots, was located nearby.  The material appears to be a wrap-around blouse of mid-length that buttoned in the front.  Two pads were recovered that appear to be shoulder pads from the blouse.  A black bra, black panties and a piece of black denim were also located.  Among the remains was a pink and green comforter with a floral design and two baby blankets.  One baby blanket was blue, white and pink in color and the other was pink and had been tied to the comforter on one corner.  The featured reconstruction is an artist's rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Maricopa County Sheriff's Office, reference case number 1997-20112 or the Maricopa County Medical Examiner's Office, reference case number 97-2152.

Skeletal remains of an unidentified male were found in a wooded area in between Dennis Ave and N Forsyth Rd in Orlando, Florida. The male had been deceased for one or more years. An anthropological exam revealed that the male suffered extensive injuries that were consistent with falling from a great height. The location where the male was found was in-line with flight patterns out of Orlando Executive Airport and Orlando International Airport. It's possible the male could have fallen from an aircraft.  The male was African American, 16-20 years old. He stood approximately 5?5' ? 5'11" tall. His weight, hair color and eye color could not be determined. He was found wearing a pair of dark colored jeans, with approximate 30" waist, jockey style underwear, and dark colored wingtip shoes size 9 1/2. The brand of shoes were the "Leather Collection" which was sold by Payless Shoes. A 1985 five cent U.S. coin was also found with the male. The anthropological exam also revealed the skeleton was particularly robust for a male of this age noting characteristics that were consistent with an occupation of a laborer. The images shown above are an enhanced image of the shoes the male was found wearing and a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist depicting what the male may have looked like in life.

Skeletal remains of an unidentified male were found on November 26, 1995 in a remote wooded area in Rock County, WI. The body was found on the bank of Turtle Creek in Bradford Township. The male had been deceased for approximately one year placing time of death in the fall/winter of 1994. The male is Caucasian and estimated to be 17-20 years old. He stood approximately 5?06? tall and had long, straight, brown hair. The male was wearing Rothco brand military-style camouflage pants, a black t-shirt bearing ?Venom? heavy metal rock band logo, black Nike Air Bound basketball sneakers (size 9 ),  and boxer style underwear with images of ?Bart Simpson?. A black Aquatech watch was found on his left wrist. Lip balm, a lighter, and cigarette filters were found inside his pant pockets. A pendant of a goat?s head handcrafted from a dinner fork was found underneath his body and a multicolored plaid flannel jacket with snap buttons was found on top of his body. The investigation revealed witnesses had observed a young male wearing similar clothing running in Turtle Creek in October, 1994 near the location where the body was discovered. It has not been confirmed that this male is in fact the unidentified male. Forensic isotope testing of his bones suggests he spent a significant amount of time in WI, MN, or MI.  Digitally enhanced images of some of the items found with the male are displayed above along with a facial reconstruction completed by a FBI Forensic Artist that depicts what the male may have looked like in life.

An unidentified female was found deceased in Apopka, Florida on April 22, 1993. Her body was found approximately one quarter mile north of highway 441 off Piedmont Wekiwa Road. She had been deceased for 3-6 weeks. The female is estimated to be in her late teens to early twenties. She had dark brown, shoulder length hair, stood between 4?11?-5?05? and weighed 100-110 pounds. An anthropological assessment suggests the female was of European or mixed ancestry with an appearance of Hispanic. It is also noted that she had Spina bifida occulta, however the female may not have been aware of this or portrayed any outward symptoms. The female had seen a dentist in life as evidenced by several dental fillings; however overall she had poor dental hygiene. Several cavities had started, tooth loose, periodontal disease and an abscess towards the bottom right of her jaw was noted. The female was found clothed wearing a large white t-shirt with the ?New York Giants? logo along with the ?Super Bowl Champions XXV? on the front with teal colored shorts. Underneath she wore a one piece light blue bathing suite.  She also had on a pair of white Gitano Casuals brand sandals, size 8 as pictured above. The female also wore several pieces of jewelry including earrings and three rings. The female had three piercings in each ear and wore the hoop earrings that are depicted above. One of the 14K gold rings was worn on her left ring finger. A second ring was gold with the center stone setting empty and the third was a gold AVON ring with a clear center stone. The female also wore fake fingernails on both hands. The images above are a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depicts what she may have looked like in life.

It?s estimated that he had been deceased for several years, likely longer than 3 years. An anthropologist examined the remains and stated they belonged to a Caucasian, possibly Hispanic male, 17-22 years old that stood approximately 5?5? tall. His hair and eye color are unknown. The male?s nose appeared slightly crooked and may have tilted to the right. Characteristics of the leg bones suggested he may have had some type of gait disturbance. The male?s lower jaw was not recovered. An exam of the upper teeth suggested that he may have endured some type of trauma to his face prior to his death that formed an abscess behind his front upper teeth. This may have caused him some pain or discomfort. The male was found wearing Levi Straus blue jeans, size 30M with a belt that had a white metal buckle. The images above are a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depicts what the male may have looked like in life. Since the lower jaw was not recovered the jaw is the artist?s interpretation and only an approximation.

On August 6, 1992, the body of an unidentified female was located in a desert area near the northwest corner of Idaho and Baseline Roads, south of US Highway 60 in Apache Junction, Arizona (Pinal County).  It is believed the Jane Doe had been deceased for approximately 3 to 5 weeks prior to recovery.  She is believed to have been between 16 and 18 years of age and was approximately 5'1".  Her race is unknown however her brown hair is microscopically similar to head hairs from known Admixed AmerIndians.  She was found wearing a pair of blue denim cut-off short pants ("Levis" brand) and a light colored pullover short-sleeved t-shirt with soccer balls on the front and back ("Team Gear" brand, size Large).  A Phoenix Transit System token inscribed with the words "Valid for one student fare" was located in her left front pants pocket.  A round piece of paper the size of a penny was found in her left front pants pocket.  The paper had a figure of Abraham Lincoln on one side and the Lincoln Memorial on the other side, both in green ink.  The Jane Doe was also found wearing a yellow metal ring with a nugget design on her left ring finger.  She had no obvious dental care and her teeth were described as "protruding".  The featured reconstruction is an artist's rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like.  The additional photos have been enhanced to aid in visual identification and may not reflect the original case file images.  Anyone with information should contact the Apache Junction Police Department, reference case number 92-3057 or the Pima County Office of the Medical Examiner, reference case number ML92-0955.

On July 19, 1992, two Hispanic males were standing at a bus stop at the corner of Vernon Avenue and Compton Boulevard in the Newton area of Los Angeles, California when they were shot by passengers in a passing vehicle.  Both victims were transported to the local hospital where they were pronounced deceased.  The first victim is believed to have been between 12 and 17 years of age.  He was 5'6" and weighed 128 lbs.  He had medium length, straight brown hair, a faint mustache, a slim build and a fair complexion.  He was found wearing blue pants, tennis shoes, a t-shirt and a black "Casio" brand watch.  He also had a scar on his upper left arm, 1/2" x 1/4" in size.  The first victim is referenced as follows: LAPD case #92-1322978, LA Coroner case #92-06560, NCMEC TA #1184146, NamUs UP 3774, NCIC U596014674.  The second victim is believed to have been between 13 and 18 years of age.  He was 5'6" and weighed 170 lbs.  The John Doe had medium length dark brown to black hair with very faint facial hair on his upper lip and chin.  He had a dark brown complexion and a scar on his left hip.  He also had a small, slightly raised 1/2" scar on his upper left thigh, and a slightly larger scar on the anterior surface of his lower left thigh.  He was also wearing blue jeans, a t-shirt and tennis shoes.  The second victim is listed as follows:  LAPD case #92-1322977, LA Coroner case #92-06614, NCMEC TA 1184478, NamUs UP 3773, NCIC U595738011.  The featured reconstructions are an artist?s renderings of what the victims may have looked like.

The decedent was likely in his early twenties, and had straight, dark brown or black hair that was approximately 5-7 inches in length. He had no facial hair except for a slight, recently-shaven mustache above his upper lip. The decedent was wearing a royal blue jacket ("BADGE FASHION-EXPLORER-1996" label, size large), a long sleeve multicolored plaid cowboy shirt (size 14), blue jeans ("MEX BEKAF" brand, size 34" x 28"), white socks, white cloth high top shoes ("CONVERSE" brand), and a yellow metal watch ("PIERRE CARDIN" brand). He also had a comb in his pocket. He had small bilateral moles on his lower face, small bilateral scars on his knees, and a 2-3 inch scar on his left elbow extending to back of left upper arm. Anyone with information should contact the Orange County Coroner's Division, reference case number 92-03027-VA.

The male had been deceased between 1-3 years prior to being found. An analysis of the skull and dentition revealed the victim is a Caucasian male, 15-18 years old. While his lower jaw was never recovered some of his upper teeth revealed that he had seen a dentist at one point in his life as several dental fillings were seen. He also had an upper left peg shaped tooth that might have been noticeable to others.  Characteristics of his bottom teeth are unknown. The facial reconstructions above were completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depicts what the male may have looked like in life.

On September 19, 1990 remains of an unidentified female were found along the Eastbound lanes of Interstate 40 in Hillsborough, Orange County, North Carolina. Her body was found over the guardrail, east of the New Hope Church Exit. The female had been deceased at this location for approximately 4-6 days. The female is Caucasian and was 14-22 years old at the time of her death. She stood 5?03? tall and weighed approximately 108 pounds. She had brown or blonde hair that was possibly color treated and cut just above her shoulders. She had a 3-inch surgical scar on her lower right abdomen that was consistent with an appendix scar. She had been treated by a dentist in life as she had fillings in three of her teeth. The female was found wearing an oversized pink sweatshirt with three cartoon bunnies on the front, a bra and ankle socks. The female was also found wearing a thin yellow metal ring on her left ring finger that appeared to be homemade and a thin twisted metal bracelet on her left wrist. Images of the ring and bracelet are above. The other images above are a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depicts what the female may have looked like in life.

On July 28th, 1990, the skeletal remains of an unidentified female were discovered in the courtyard of an abandoned apartment complex on the 1200 block of South Western Avenue in Los Angeles, California. Based on the condition of the remains, the decedent is believed to have been deceased a minimum of three years prior to discovery, and most likely had been deceased about two decades prior to discovery. The decedent is believed to have been of Asian race, and likely an admixture of Asian and African American. She was found wearing blue and white-striped shorts. Also found with the remains was a yellow, green, and red blanket. She had one alloy dental filling on an upper right molar. One of her lower right central incisors were twisted, which would have been noticeable when she spoke.  The reconstruction featured above is an artist?s rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Los Angeles County Coroner, reference case number 90-7438, or the Los Angeles Police Department-Wilshire Division and reference case# 90-07-31284.

On June 8, 1990, the body of an unidentified male was found in a holding tank at a water treatment plant in the area of South 22nd Street and Lincoln Street in Phoenix, Arizona.  The John Doe is believed to have been between 16 and 19 years of age.  He was approximately 6'0", had brown hair and is described as both Caucasian and Hispanic.  Clothing items found near the body include a blue tank top which reads "Colorado University Boulder", a white sweatshirt with 1988 Olympic logos, white tennis shoes with black laces (size 12) and black pants.  Found in the pockets of the pants was a matchbook and papers associated with "Barley's Restaurant".  It should be noted that this clothing was found near the body and it is uncertain whether it belonged to the decedent.  The featured reconstruction was provided by the Phoenix Police Department and is an artist's rendering of what the John Doe may have looked like.  The additional photos have been enhanced to aid in visual identification and may not reflect the original case file images.  Anyone with information should contact the Phoenix Police Department, reference case number 00330884.

Skeletal remains of a young child were found on December 18, 1988 in a rural wooded area in Ware County, Georgia. The child?s remains were found concealed inside a duffle bag that was placed inside a suitcase, and further concealed inside an old television cabinet. It?s estimated the child had been deceased for one to two months before being found. The child is a black female, 3-4 years old. She had black hair pulled into a pony tail secured on the top of her head by a brown rubber band. She was found wearing a white knit pullover shirt with a red pony emblem on the upper left chest, white thermal pajama bottoms with maroon trim, and a disposable diaper. The child?s ears were pierced but no earrings were found with her. Displayed above are digital reconstructions of the child?s clothing and a facial reconstruction created by a NCMEC Forensic Artist that depicts what the child may have looked like in life.

On December 15, 1988, the body of an unidentified male was found in a culvert under a bridge off County Road 22 (now known as Eldorado Parkway at approximately the 9100 block),  mile east of FM 289 in Frisco, Texas (Collin County). The decedent is believed to have been deceased for approximately 24 hours at time of discovery. He had straight black hair, approximately 3  inches in length, and a faint black mustache above upper lip.  The decedent was found wearing a black motorcycle jacket, a short sleeve grey and white striped shirt, green-grey corduroy jeans, a black belt with a red/black/gold buckle, grey socks, and black loafer shoes (?Italians? brand, size 5). He was found wearing the following jewelry:  two black rubber rings on his left ring finger, a yellow to gold colored watch on left wrist, and a red and green string style bracelet also on his left wrist. The decedent was also found with a disposable lighter, a pack of cigarettes (?Marlboro Light? brand), and chapstick in the pockets of his jacket. He had scars on his left forearm, right forearm and on his chest.  He also had two tattoos: the first on his upper left arm of a heart with a cross and arrow through the heart with letters ?R y A? in the middle (possible translation to ?R and A? in Spanish, shown above), the second tattoo is a cross on the front of the left forearm. His top right central incisor tooth is also outlined in a silver cap. The photo featured above is a computer generated image (provided by the Texas Rangers) of what the John Doe may have looked like.  The photo of the tattoo has been enhanced to aid in visual identification and may not reflect the original case file image.

On November 16, 1987  an unidentified female was found in a heavily wooded area in Eureka, SC. The body was found approximately 1 1/2  miles south of the intersection of Highway 191 (Johnston Highway) and Highway 208 (Mt. Calvary Road) near Shaw's Creek .  It was estimated that she had been deceased for 1 to 5 years.  The female was multi-racial with predominately black heritage and a significant mix of Indian or Asian.  She may also have been Caribbean.  It was estimated that the female was in her late teens to early twenties, she stood between 5'8" and 5'10" tall, and she weighed approximately 150 to 160 lbs.  An anthropological assessment of the female?s bones showed a healed fracture on the left side of her nose.  She may also have had an old healed injury to her right knee.  The female's first molar on the lower right side had been removed earlier in life. She also had a pronounced overbite (buck teeth).  No personal items or clothing were found with the female.  The image above is a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC forensic artist and depicts what the female may have looked like in life.

On November 6, 1987 an unidentified male was driving north bound on Interstate 75 in a stolen black 1986 Chevrolet Corvette while being pursued by law enforcement. During the pursuit the vehicle crashed in Alachua County, FL. The vehicle ignited into flames upon the crash leaving the unidentified male unrecognizable. The investigation revealed that the vehicle had originally been stolen from a car dealership in Clearwater, Florida and witnesses remember seeing the vehicle at a gas station in Brooksville, Florida shortly before the accident. Witnesses described the driver as being a white male with Italian features, dark, medium length hair, slender build and stated he was wearing blue jeans but no shirt. A Forensic Anthropologist examined the male and reported he was white, 16-18 years old and stood 5?9? ? 6?01? tall. Several of his teeth were damaged in the accident but one tooth had a recent root canal where the treatment may not have been completed. The images above are a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depicts what the male may have looked like in life. A significant portion of the facial bones were destroyed in the accident. The missing portion was reconstructed by a Forensic Anthropologist and may not fully represent the male?s true facial features.

An unidentified female was found deceased on February 6, 1986 in Tampa, Florida. Her body was found along 2nd Ave between 31st and 34th street in an industrial area of Tampa. She had likely been deceased three to eight weeks prior to being found. The female is estimated to have been 16-22 years old at the time of death. She stood approximately 5'02" tall. She was African American and had "kinky brown hair" according to the original police report. An anthropological exam revealed that the female had sustained injuries to the left side of her head and nose earlier in life which likely caused her to have a deviated septum. Several congenital defects were also seen in her spine but it is unknown whether they would have caused her any physical discomfort. The female may have even been unaware of the defects. The female?s teeth were in very poor condition and some of the untreated teeth were likely causing her pain. Chemical isotope analysis has suggested she was most likely born and raised in Florida. The images displayed are a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depicts what the female may have looked like in life.

On September 14, 1984 an unidentified female was found on Eppirt Street in East Orange, New Jersey. The female had only been deceased a few hours. The female is black and estimated to have been 15-20 years old at the time of her death. She had black hair and brown eyes. She stood approximately 5'05"-5'07" tall and weighed between 135-155 pounds. The female had multiple scars. She had a scar on her left cheek under her eye approximately half-inch long, a three-inch scar on her neck in the middle towards the left side, and multiple scars on the palm side of both forearms. The condition of the female's fingernails suggested that she was a nail bitter. She was found fully clothed, wearing jeans, a gray sweater, socks, and a white bra. She was also wearing four rings: a silver-colored ring with the letter "Y", a gold-colored ring with 21 white-colored stones, a plane gold-colored ring, and a black-colored rubber ring. Images of the clothing and jewelry are not available. The female?s ear lobes were both pierced. Dental fillings were observed indicating she was treated by a dentist during life. The images displayed are a facial reconstruction created by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depicts what the female may have looked like in life.

Skeletal remains of an unidentified female were found in Fort Lauderdale, Florida on September 19, 1983. She was found in a wooded area along Route 27 just south of the Palm Beach County line in Broward County. The female was not facially recognizable and estimated to have been deceased for several months up to a year. The female is Caucasian but might have had mixed ancestry. She is estimated to be 11-19 years old and stood between 5?00? and 5?04? tall. She had brown or auburn colored medium length hair. Her toenails were painted with purple polish and she was wearing a yellow gold chain with a real seashell pendant when she was found. A digitally enhanced image of the necklace is featured above. An anthropological exam of the bones revealed that the female had Spina Bifida in her back but was possibly unaware of the condition because it was asymptomatic. The female also had osteoarthritis in her left hip and left leg that was most likely a result from a previous traumatic injury and possibly produced a chronic aching and altered range of motion in her left leg joints. The female also suffered a fracture to her left ankle earlier in life that may or may not have been associated to the osteoarthritis. The female had also been treated by a dentist in life as several fillings were seen her in teeth. The male was found wearing brown slacks with a 28? waist and 30? inseam.  He was also wearing a faded Hawaiian themed sport shirt.  A Converse right shoe with red trim on the sole, size 7.5, was also found. The left shoe was not found.  The image above is a facial reconstruction provided by Forensic Artist with the Eden Project and depicts what the male may have looked like in life.

On November 4, 1982 human remains of a young female were discovered inside a city dumpster along N Main Street in Freeport, New York (Nassau County). The location was near the intersection of N Main Street and Mount Joy Ave. The female had been deceased for an extended period of time, but less than one year. She is estimated to have been in her teens or twenties at the time of her death. Her hair color, hair style, and eye color are unknown. She stood approximately 5'00"-5'03" tall. Her race is unknown, but possibly Caucasian with African admixture. She was found wearing a short sleeve yellow, pink, and blue striped sweater that zippered up the front. Three necklaces were also found with her. One was an 18K necklace with an opal pendant, another was a metal necklace with yellow heart pendant with the letter "K" in the center; and a badly tarnished "snake" chain with a small green stone. Digitally enhanced images of the opal necklace and sweater are depicted above. The other images are a facial reconstruction created by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depict what the female may have looked like in life.

Skeletal remains of an unidentified female were found in Frederick, Maryland on August 24, 1982. The female's body was found inside a trunk, also known as a footlocker, a few feet off a gravel road in Gambrills State Park in the Catochin Mountains. She had been deceased for several months placing death in early Spring, 1982. The female is believed to be Caucasian, in her late teens or twenties. She stood 5'3"-5'05" tall and had shoulder length, slightly wavy dark brown hair. A Forensic Anthropologist observed skeletal features in the lower back and feet that may have been related to a previous injury or injuries. The female also had extensive dental work completed that consisted of several fillings, root canals, and crowns. No clothing or jewelry was found with the female. The images displayed are a facial reconstruction created by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depict what the female may have looked like in life.

FOUL PLAY SUSPECTED.

On June 26, 1982, the decomposed body of an unidentified white male was located in the Snake River near the mouth of the Grand Ronde River in Nez Perce County, Idaho.  It is suspected the John Doe had been deceased for at least 2-3 weeks.  The John Doe is believed to have been between 18 and 22 years of age.  He was 5'11" and between 145 and 160 lbs.  He had straight dark brown to black hair (3-4 inches in length).  Eye color is unknown.  He had a 2" scar on his right ankle.  No dental work was apparent in the teeth.  The John Doe was found wearing "Britannia" jeans over blue swimming trunks with red and white stripes down the sides of the trunks ("California Sun" brand), white socks and blue brief-style underwear (size S).  It is noted the palms of both of his hands exhibited corns or calluses, possibly suggesting manual labor.  The featured composite is an artist's rendering of what the John Doe may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Nez Perce County Sheriff's Office, reference case number 82-1141 or the Nez Perce County Coroner's Office, reference case number 82-037.

On November 17, 1980, the remains a young female were located in a shallow grave in a remote desert area off Route 66 in Ludlow, California (San Bernardino County).  It is believed the she had been deceased between 1 and 6 months.  The Jane Doe is believed to be a Caucasian and between 17 and 22 years of age.  She was between 5?5" and 5?8" and approximately 115 lbs.  She had light brown/red hair.  A yellow metal 10K ring (size 7) with 7 glass stones was found with the Jane Doe.  The center stone was missing.  The Jane Doe had multiple gaps in her smile, both top and bottom, with congenitally missing lateral incisors and a retained primary right canine. Her smile was incredibly distinctive and would have be recognizable by those who knew her.  The body of an unidentified male was also found in the grave.  The John Doe is believed to be a white male between 21 and 30 years of age.  He is believed to have been approximately 5'4".  He had long brown hair (approximately 12 to 15 inches) tied into a pony tail.  He had a tattoo of Egyptian Ankh and his left ear was pierced.  A white metal "Ankh" earring was found on the John Doe.  The featured reconstruction is an artist?s rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the San Bernardino County Sheriff?s Department ? Coroner Division reference case number 56773.

On November 5, 1980 the unidentified remains of a female were found along Interstate 95, north of the Volusia-Brevard County line in Daytona Beach, FL. Her race was an admixture, both black and white, with probable Hispanic origin. She was estimated to have stood 5'7" - 5'11" tall. Her weight, hair and eye color could not be determined. An anthropological exam revealed she may have performed repetitive activity with her arms and shoulders during her lifetime. The female had seen a dentist in life as several dental fillings were seen, however the fillings were of poor quality and the material used to fill the teeth was consistent with older material that was no longer being used in the United States. The female was found wearing a red t-shirt, red shorts with blue trim, pair of green plastic shoes size 8, and possibly had a white handkerchief and some change on her. The image above is a facial reconstruction created by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depicts what she may have looked like in life.

On Sunday, March 16, 1980, the body of an unidentified black female was found in the waters of the San Francisco Bay in Fremont, California (Alameda County). The Jane Doe is believed to have been between 18 and 25 years of age.  She was approximately 5?4" and 112 lbs.  She had medium length black hair and brown eyes.  Her fingernails were long and clean and she had gold caps on her lower first molars.  The Jane Doe was found wearing blue denim pants ("Levi Strauss & Co." brand), a brown leather belt (size 32) with four Indian Head Nickels in the form of studs mounted on the belt, calf-length brown socks, white panties and a white bra (size 34B).  She was also wearing a yellow metal ladies Timex watch on her left wrist.  The watch was water resistant and had a brown/gold color face with yellow metal raised marks in lieu of hour numbers.  The featured reconstruction is an artist's rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like in life.  Anyone with information should contact the Fremont Police Department, reference case number 00316072 or the Alameda County Coroner's Office reference case number 1980-0637.

The decedent was found wearing a long sleeve orange-colored shirt with the sleeves rolled up to his elbows, brown trousers with no back pockets, and size 6.5 black harness boots. He had a burn scar on his left hip, a scar on his right knee, and a circular vaccination scar on his upper left arm. The reconstruction featured above is an artist's rendering of what the decedent may have looked like.  The additional photos have been enhanced to aid in visual identification and may not reflect the original case file images.  Anyone with information regarding this case, please contact the Harris County Institute of Forensic Sciences, reference case number ML79-2203, or the Houston Police Department and reference case number P-14427.

This unidentified female was found off the roadway in the 5600 block of Dogwood Road near Lorraine Park Cemetery in Baltimore County, Maryland. A light brown leather shoe with twine used as a shoelace was found nearby and suspected to have been worn by the female. On April 11, 1976, the remains of an unidentified female were found in a dry creek bed in a rural area approximately 90 feet west of Lopez Canyon Road in San Fernando, California. Based on the condition of the remains, it is believed the Jane Doe was likely deceased one week prior to discovery. She was approximately 20 years of age with a small build and was estimated to have weighed between 100-120 lbs. The decedent was found wearing purple bell-bottom pants (?MALE? brand), a tan long sleeve multicolored print blouse worn midriff-style with rust-colored tree figures and elastic cuffs (?STYLED IN CALIFORNIA? brand). She was also found with black 4? heel clog shoes with a heavy leather strap and a brown suede jacket with a white wool collar and white cuffs (?LONDONTOWN BY CHECKPOINT? brand). She had dirty blonde roots to light brown hair approximately 18 inches in length that reached her middle back and plucked eyebrows. The decedent had a full silver cap on left upper first molar. She also had a vertical scare below her right knee cap approximately 1? in length.  The reconstruction featured above is an artist?s rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Los Angeles County Coroner, reference case number 76-4631.

An unidentified male was found deceased near Miami on March 21, 1976.  He washed ashore on a small island in the Intercoastal Waterway just north of Sunny Isles Boulevard. He had been deceased a few weeks once he was found. The male is estimated to be 15-25 years old. He stood approximately 5?11? tall and weighed around 150-160 pounds. He had shoulder length straight black hair. The male had received extensive dental care in life. His upper three front teeth had been extracted a long time prior to his death and it?s possible he had worn a partial denture plate; however one was not found with him. Several fillings were also seen in his teeth. The male was found wearing a light colored long-sleeve button down shirt, denim jeans with a lace up fly closure, and dark brown leather boots. The male also had both earlobes pierced once with one gold colored hooped earring in each ear. Digitally reconstructed images of the boots and the jeans are featured above and were created by a NCMEC Forensic Artist.

On March 9, 1976 skeletal remains of a young child were found in basement storage of an apartment complex on Winston Drive in Greece, New York within Monroe County. The child was found wrapped inside a large tarp inside a blue metal footlocker wearing a light blue pajama top and a plastic diaper secured by 2 stainless steel diaper pins. It?s estimated that the child had been deceased 6 months to 1 year, or possibly longer. The child had short brown hair and is estimated to be 3-5 years old. The child had a skull abnormality to the back left region of his head. While it is unknown what caused the abnormality it likely occurred a significant amount of time before the child?s death and may have caused or been associated with other health problems that affected his nutrition and growth. The child likely could not walk and may have had developmental deficiencies. Geochemical analysis of his remains indicate he may not have been local to the New York area, having spent the first years of his life in the U.S. Northwest and the last years of his life in the U.S. Southeast.

A dark blue sweater/jacket with snaps, a red, green, black and gray vertically striped sweater/jacket liner and brown hiking boots with hooks and eyelets (size 7-7.5) were located near the remains. Anyone with information should contact the San Mateo County Coroner?s office, reference case number 75-00936.

On August 9, 1973, the skeletal remains of an unidentified male were recovered in Houston, Texas. Based on the condition of the remains, the decedent was likely deceased for 12 months or more prior to recovery. The decedent was white, possibly with Hispanic admixture.  He had brown hair approximately 7 inches in length (from the crown). He was found with belted ?Catalina? swim trunks with vertical red, turquoise, gold, and dark blue stripes, with the letter ?C? on the silver buckle (shown above) and a khaki-colored long sleeved t-shirt that tied in the front. The shirt had a large blue and white peace symbol and the letters ?USMC?, and ?L84MF? written underneath the peace symbol. He was also found with dark blue corduroys with a 32 inch waist and a 30 inch inseam, a knotted leather ankle bracelet, and brown leather cowboy boots that were 12 inches in length and had the word ?NEOLITE? on the heel.  Examination revealed that the boy had a mild form of spina bifida which may have caused him lower back pain or possibly affected his stride; however, it may not have produced any noticeable symptoms. John Houston Doe is the last known unidentified victim of Dean Arnold Corll, aka ?The Candy Man?, who abducted and murdered at least 29 young males in the Houston area between 1970 and 1973. The reconstruction featured above is an artist?s rendering of what he may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Harris County Institute of Forensic Sciences, reference case number ML73-3356.

On April 22, 1973 the body of an unidentified white male was found along the Terminal Island Freeway in Wilmington, California.  The John Doe is believed to have been between 17 and 25 years of age.  He was between 5'2" and 5'10" and weighed between 135 and 160 lbs.  He had brown, wavy/curly hair, approximately 5 inches in length, brown eyes and a thin/fine mustache.  He possibly had a small mole on the right side of his neck below his right ear.  The John Doe had a surgical scar on the lower abdomen just above the pubic region, consistent with a cystotomy procedure.  The John Doe is believed to have been a victim of serial killer Randy Kraft.  The featured reconstruction is an artist's rendering of what the John Doe may have looked like. Anyone with information should contact the Los Angeles County Coroner's Office, reference case number 1973-06955.

On June 26, 1972, an unidentified white male was struck by a vehicle east of the Highway 183 overpass on I-40 in Clinton, Oklahoma (Custer County).  The John Doe is believed to have been between 16 and 20 years of age.  He had long dark brown hair (less than shoulder length) and hazel eyes.  The John Doe had unshaven faint hair growth along the sides of his cheeks.  He was found wearing a blue double-knit shirt ("Never Iron brand" by CAMPUS), blue jeans, a brown leather 30-inch belt with ?Captain?s? buckle, tall brown leather boots (size 9-9.5) with a 1 inch strap with brass rings on either side and a blue armband on his left arm made of denim material.  He was also wearing a white gold-colored ?promise? ring with ?TC968? engraved on the inside.  A pack of ?Marlboro? cigarettes with a St. Louis, Missouri stamp #42289 was found in his pocket.  A sheet of paper with the dates June 16 through June 30 and the word ?Mollincrodt? or ?Mellincrodt? written on it was also recovered with the body.  The featured composite is an artist?s rendering of what the John Doe may have looked like in life.  Anyone with information should contact the Oklahoma Office of the Chief Medical Examiner and reference case number 721300.

An unidentified male was found deceased on May 7, 1972 in Volusia County, Florida. He was found floating in a pond near Indian Lake Road. He had been deceased for 3-4 days before being found. The boy is Caucasian, 11-14 years old. He stood approximately 5'2" tall and had dark brown wavy hair. No dental fillings were observed in his teeth. He had a benign bone tumor in his right leg that is common in male children and asymptomatic. He also had a congenital condition where bones in his feet fused together but also would have been asymptotic. The boy was found wearing a blue denim jacket, a red and white short-sleeved striped shirt, grey tweed pants, brown dress socks, and one black loafer dress shoe with a silver buckle on the side (size 8 1/2). A black leather wallet was also found in the left rear pocket of his pants. Digitally enhanced images of some of the clothing is displayed above. The other images shown are a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist  and depicts what the boy may have looked like in life.

On January 1, 1972 at approximately 3:35 AM the body of an unidentified white male was found on the northbound lanes of I-5/Santa Ana Freeway in Anaheim, California (Orange County).  It is believed he jumped or fell from the Euclid Street Bridge and was struck by multiple vehicles. The John Doe is believed to have been between 18 and 23 years of age.  He is described as being well-developed and well-nourished.  He was between 5'10" and 6'3" and between 180 and 200 lbs.  The John Doe had reddish/brown shoulder-length, straight hair and hazel eyes.  He was found wearing a brown velour jacket, brown brushed cotton trousers ("Viceroy Jeans" brand), a white and lavender floral shirt and a wide brown leather belt.  He was also wearing a silver ring with an inlaid floral design on his left pinky and a silver puzzle type of ring (one band) on his right pinky.  It is noted this ring was originally sold as a 4-piece set.  The John Doe was not wearing shoes and no shoes were recovered at the scene.  The John Doe's blood type is O+  The featured images have been digitally enhanced and may not reflect the original case file photos.  Anyone with information should contact the Orange County Sheriff's Department - Coroner's Office, reference case number 72-00006-S.
Orange County Sheriff's Department, Coroner Division: 714-647-7400

On December 6, 1971 an unidentified female was found in Galloway Township, New Jersey near the Garden State Parkway. Her body was found in a wooded area off Jimmie Leeds Road. The female had been deceased for several months prior to being found. The female is estimated to be 12-18 years old but likely on the younger side closer to age of 12-14. She was petite at about 5?02? tall and around 115 pounds. Her hair was possibly auburn and shoulder length. She was found wearing a blue polo shirt, bell bottom slacks with multiple colored vertical stripes, and brown leather sandals. She also wore a wide leather band bracelet with small brass eyelets all around the band. Attached to the bracelet through some of the eyelets was a small watch. The watch did not appear to have been originally attached to the leather band but secured separately. Inside the female's pants was a key to a local motel along the Garden State Parkway. The images above is an enhanced photograph of the bracelet the female was wearing along with a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and another one completed by a NJSP Forensic Artist. Both reconstructions depict what the female may have looked like in life.
